<p>The Korean version of a college admissions exam, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/College_Scholastic_Ability_Test" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CSAT</a>, administered last month, had several questions about Immanuel Kant. <span id="more-55765"></span></p>
<div id="attachment_55770" style="width: 695px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-55770" class=" wp-image-55770" src="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/kant-digital-copy.jpg" alt="" width="685" height="450" srcset="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/kant-digital-copy.jpg 1713w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/kant-digital-copy-300x197.jpg 300w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/kant-digital-copy-1024x673.jpg 1024w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/kant-digital-copy-768x505.jpg 768w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/kant-digital-copy-1536x1010.jpg 1536w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/kant-digital-copy-400x263.jpg 400w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 685px) 100vw, 685px" /><p id="caption-attachment-55770" class="wp-caption-text">[image made with <a href="https://ascii.iapetus11.me/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">To-ASCII</a> and Photoshop]</p></div>According to reports in the <a href="https://www.chosun.com/english/opinion-en/2025/11/27/U3M3VTUFCFG7XGYWYPVDCDYN3U/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Chosun Daily</em></a>, the German philosopher was &#8220;tormenting students&#8221; in various sections of the exam, and there was a fair amount of discussion of the questions online after the test sessions.</p>
<p>One of the questions (number 17) was about Kant&#8217;s theory of personal identity and ended up generating some controversy.</p>
<p>Philosopher <a href="https://philpeople.org/profiles/chunghyoung-lee" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Lee Chung-hyung</a> (Pohang University of Science and Technology), according to another <em>Chosun </em><em>Daily </em><a href="https://www.chosun.com/english/national-en/2025/11/19/WOLGO6GCUNBORKU6SSUZC55GJI/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">article</a>, posted a message to a student discussion board saying, &#8220;I attempted the Kant-related question from the CSAT Korean language exam and found that Question 17 appeared to have no correct answer.&#8221;</p>
<p>Question 17 was among several questions based on a passage summarizing the views of Kant and other philosophers.</p>
<p>Here is the passage and questions 14, 15, and 16, with a translation of uncertain quality by Google (it can&#8217;t seem to translate some names). You should be able to click to enlarge the image, though even enlarged, the quality is not great. A better translation, by ChatGPT 5.1, follows the image.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-55766 aligncenter" src="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/csat-kant-passage-translation.png" alt="" width="1561" height="1191" srcset="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/csat-kant-passage-translation.png 1561w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/csat-kant-passage-translation-300x229.png 300w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/csat-kant-passage-translation-1024x781.png 1024w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/csat-kant-passage-translation-768x586.png 768w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/csat-kant-passage-translation-1536x1172.png 1536w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/csat-kant-passage-translation-400x305.png 400w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1561px) 100vw, 1561px" /></p>
<p>Here&#8217;s ChatGPT&#8217;s translation. I&#8217;ll note that I&#8217;m not sure it correctly identified the philosophers discussed (informed comments on that welcome):</p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="222" data-end="289"><em><strong data-start="225" data-end="289">[14~17] Read the following passage and answer the questions.</strong></em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="291" data-end="957"><em>Philosophers commonly describe humans as “self-reflective” or “creatures who think about themselves.” This idea of human distinctiveness is grounded in the fact that humans possess a capacity for self-awareness distinct from that of other animals. We typically believe that only humans can think about themselves “as themselves”—that I perceive myself as “me,” distinct from others. This ability for self-awareness has long been regarded as a defining feature of human beings. When a person thinks about themselves from a first-person standpoint—“I am doing X,” “I am such-and-such kind of person”—that stance is thought to arise from an inner, mental perspective.</em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="959" data-end="1417"><em>However, we do not say “I think” merely because a subjective awareness arises. If that alone were sufficient, there would be no need for the self as a separate entity. In fact, what enables self-awareness is not simply an internal mental scene but the structure that allows the representation of oneself. In that sense, what explains self-thinking is not an independent inner realm but a system that allows the subject to be distinguished from the world.</em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="1419" data-end="1945"><em>This view rejects the claim that self-awareness is grounded in some mysterious inner realm. According to this view, “I think” can be explained by the general cognitive capacities we all possess. It may appear that I can step back and reflect on myself, but such reflection can be fully explained through ordinary cognitive operations. Proponents of representational views argue that what makes self-awareness possible is not a special inner entity but the conceptual structure that enables one to represent oneself as oneself.</em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="1947" data-end="2465"><em>[A]</em><br data-start="1950" data-end="1953" /><em>Some philosophers criticize this view, arguing that it merely explains the representation of the self but not the experience of being oneself. According to them, the representational account treats self-awareness as merely the result of a cognitive mechanism, thus overlooking the felt, experiential aspect of self-awareness. They argue that although representationalism can explain how a subject distinguishes itself from the world, it cannot explain the immediate sense of “mineness” present in experience.</em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="2467" data-end="2970"><em>Because representationalists focus on explaining the subject’s ability to distinguish itself from the world, they treat self-awareness as arising from the structural conditions for representation. But experientialists claim that this misses something crucial: that the sense of self is not something constructed by a representational mechanism but rather present directly in experience. For experientialists, the “I” is not something constructed; rather, one encounters oneself directly in experience.</em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="2972" data-end="3728"><em>Sartre accepts part of the representationalist argument—that the subject distinguishes itself from the world—but he rejects the claim that the sense of self must therefore be constructed by representation. Instead, Sartre claims that the sense of self is given immediately in experience. Therefore, representationalist explanations cannot account for the pre-reflective aspect of self-awareness. However, Sartre does not claim that the self is a metaphysical entity. Rather, he claims that the sense of self “emerges” from conscious experience itself. According to Sartre, self-awareness occurs even before one intentionally reflects on oneself. Because of this, representational mechanisms are unnecessary for explaining the origin of the sense of self.</em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="3730" data-end="4566"><em>Heidegger also argues that the human being is not fundamentally a subject who represents the world. Instead, the human being is an entity who always already exists in a meaningful situation, acting and responding within that world. In this perspective, self-awareness is not something that arises from inner mental representation. Rather, humans experience themselves through their everyday activities and relations. We encounter ourselves not as independent subjects but as beings immersed in meaningful contexts. For that reason, the experiential self is not a detached observer but an agent situated within the world. According to Heidegger, to understand self-awareness, we must not begin by separating a subjective self from the world but must instead examine how the human being already operates meaningfully within its situation.</em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="4568" data-end="4946"><em>Thus, experientialists reject the representationalist claim that self-awareness arises from representational structures. Instead, they argue that the sense of self emerges directly in experience, prior to reflection. Although they agree that humans can reflect on themselves, they claim that the foundation for such reflection lies in this pre-reflective experiential awareness.</em></p>
<hr style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="4948" data-end="4951" />
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="4953" data-end="5012"><em><strong data-start="4956" data-end="5012">14. Which statement is NOT supported by the passage?</strong></em></p>
