<hr />
<p>Even before getting to the controversial question 17, one might pause to note just how sophisticated a text this is to ask high school students aboiut. It is, reportedly, one of the &#8220;high-difficulty items&#8221; on the exam. I could not imagine anything like this being on the US version of the SAT.</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s question 17, again first with a translation by Google, followed by a translation by ChatGPT:</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-55767" src="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/csat-kant-q17-translated.png" alt="" width="1520" height="1295" srcset="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/csat-kant-q17-translated.png 1520w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/csat-kant-q17-translated-300x256.png 300w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/csat-kant-q17-translated-1024x872.png 1024w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/csat-kant-q17-translated-768x654.png 768w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/11/csat-kant-q17-translated-400x341.png 400w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1520px) 100vw, 1520px" /></p>
<p>Here&#8217;s ChatGPT&#8217;s translation of question 17:</p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="126" data-end="245"><em><strong>17. Based on the passage, which of the following is the most appropriate interpretation of [View]? [3 points]</strong></em></p>
<hr style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="247" data-end="250" />
<p style="text-align: center; padding-left: 80px;" data-start="252" data-end="265"><em><strong data-start="255" data-end="265">〈View〉</strong></em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="267" data-end="288"><em><strong data-start="271" data-end="286">(Speaker A)</strong></em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="289" data-end="851"><em>Let us imagine scanning the consciousness occurring in the brain and reproducing it as a program. In that case, the original self and the reproduced consciousness would not be the same person. This is because the consciousness occurring in the brain arises from the entire living body of the organism. In other words, consciousness reproduced as a program cannot be considered a person. A mere “thinking me” inside a program cannot guarantee the continuity of personal identity, and the living body must be included among the constitutive elements of a person.</em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="853" data-end="874"><em><strong data-start="857" data-end="872">(Speaker B)</strong></em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="875" data-end="1289"><em>I disagree. The consciousness reproduced as a program is the same person as the original. It is simply that the program does not have a biological body, but the cognitive functions carried out by the brain and by the program do not differ in any essential way. The continuity of personal identity does not depend on the nature of the body but should be judged on the basis of the sameness of cognitive functions.</em></p>
<hr style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="1291" data-end="1294" />
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="1296" data-end="1317"><em><strong data-start="1299" data-end="1317">Answer Choices</strong></em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="1319" data-end="1463"><em><strong data-start="1319" data-end="1324">①</strong> According to Locke’s theory, Speaker A’s claim—that the consciousness reproduced as a program could become a person—would be acceptable.</em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="1465" data-end="1610"><em><strong data-start="1465" data-end="1470">②</strong> According to Strawson’s theory, Speaker B’s claim—that an existence lacking a body cannot be considered a person—would not be acceptable.</em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="1612" data-end="1815"><em><strong data-start="1612" data-end="1617">③</strong> According to Kant’s theory as it has been traditionally understood, Speaker A’s claim—that “the thinking ‘I’ alone” does not guarantee the continuity of personal identity—would not be acceptable.</em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="1817" data-end="2040"><em><strong data-start="1817" data-end="1822">④</strong> According to Kant’s theory, the continuity of personal identity can be determined by the sameness of cognitive functions, without needing to posit any underlying substance, so Speaker B’s view would be acceptable.</em></p>
<p style="padding-left: 40px;" data-start="2042" data-end="2254"><em><strong data-start="2042" data-end="2047">⑤</strong> According to Locke’s theory, because cognitive functions that can be performed identically even in a non-human existence constitute the criterion for personal identity, Speaker B’s view would be acceptable.</em></p>
<hr />
<p><em>Chosun Daily </em><a href="https://www.chosun.com/english/national-en/2025/11/19/WOLGO6GCUNBORKU6SSUZC55GJI/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">reports</a> on Professor Lee&#8217;s critique, however some of its force may have been lost in translation:</p>
<p class=" article-body__content article-body__content-text | text--black text font--size-sm-18 font--size-md-18 font--primary" style="padding-left: 40px;"><em>The question presented the argument of &#8220;Person A,&#8221; who claimed that if consciousness occurring in the brain is scanned and reproduced via a program, the original self and the reproduced consciousness are not the same person. Test-takers were then asked to select the most appropriate response demonstrating an understanding of this argument.</em></p>
<p class=" article-body__content article-body__content-text | text--black text font--size-sm-18 font--size-md-18 font--primary" style="padding-left: 40px;"><em>The Korea Institute for Curriculum and Evaluation designated option 3 as the correct answer: &#8220;According to the prominent view before Kant, Person A’s stance that the persistence of the ‘thinking self’ alone does not guarantee personal identity would be incorrect.&#8221;</em></p>
<p class=" article-body__content article-body__content-text | text--black text font--size-sm-18 font--size-md-18 font--primary" style="padding-left: 40px;"><em>However, Professor Lee argued in his post that option 3 cannot be the correct answer. The passage states, &#8220;Before Kant, the prominent view explaining personal identity was that the soul, as the ‘thinking self,’ persists as a single subject over time.&#8221; Professor Lee asserted that since the reproduced consciousness via a scan program does not meet the condition of being a &#8220;single subject,&#8221; Person A’s argument—that the persistence of the &#8220;thinking self&#8221; alone does not guarantee personal identity—is valid.</em></p>
<p class=" article-body__content article-body__content-text | text--black text font--size-sm-18 font--size-md-18 font--primary" style="padding-left: 40px;"><em>Additionally, Professor Lee stated, &#8220;While one might think the question can be solved using the logical structure ‘if a = b and a has property C, then b also has C,’ this approach is actually flawed.&#8221; He explained, &#8220;Person A discusses the ‘thinking self’ but not the soul, so a connection between the two is necessary. The only link provided in the passage is the phrase ‘the thinking self, the soul,’ but this expression does not appear anywhere in the passage or the answer choices.&#8221; He emphasized that the argument cannot be simplified in this way.</em></p>
<p>It was <a href="https://www.chosun.com/english/opinion-en/2025/11/27/U3M3VTUFCFG7XGYWYPVDCDYN3U/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">reported</a> that Lee &#8220;explained his reasoning over eight A4 pages&#8221; and shared them with other philosophers, one of whom (unnamed) responded: &#8220;The passage and question contain logical leaps&#8230; Nonetheless, those who understood Kant’s pre-existing views and the answer choices in the passage could likely solve it.&#8221;</p>
<p>Discussion, especially from Kant scholars and Korean-speaking philosophers, welcome.</p><p>The post <a href="https://dailynous.com/2025/12/01/kantraversy-over-korean-sat-question/">Kantraversy Over Korean SAT Question</a> first appeared on <a href="https://dailynous.com">Daily Nous</a>.</p>